Many msg files I have worked with have contained a file with a compressed rich text format body (compression known as LZFu. See [https://github.com/delimitry/compressed_rtf](https://github.com/delimitry/compressed_rtf) for a python module that can decompress the data) inside of them. It is stored in the file "__substg1.0_10090102". I have personally added the property to the Message class like so:
```
@property
def compressedRtf(self):
	try:
		return self._compressedRtf
	except Exception:
		self._compressedRtf = self._getStream('__substg1.0_10090102')
		return self._compressedRtf

```

I am just requesting this so that I can continue to get updates without having to manually add this back every time, as well as to start the framework for creating a function that saves the body as an rtf file if the user so chooses. Right now I am using this as part of my own script that converts msg files into pdfs and it requires the compressed rtf body to do so.

((Sorry if this is not the proper way to make a request like this. I don't know what the proper way to do so would be.))

Edit: see [https://github.com/TheElementalOfCreation/msg-extractor/blob/master/ExtractMsg.py](https://github.com/TheElementalOfCreation/msg-extractor/blob/master/ExtractMsg.py) for edited file. Also includes additions to make it so that attachments can be saved by their content id if the user wants to.
